Accordingly Strabo travelled in books even more than in countries. In his account of Transalpine Gaul he makes use of Caesar, of Aristode and Posidonius, of the historiam Ephorus, Timaeus, Polybius, Timagenes, and Asinius Pollio, of the travellers Pytheas and Artemidorus, not to mention quotations from Aeschylus and Euripides. Of these, spart from Caesar, the authority upon whom he relied most is Posidonius. That philosopher had himself visited Gaul and studied the manners of the inhabitants. He died about s. c. 51.
